The '''black-and-yellow broadbill''' ('''''Eurylaimus ochromalus''''') is a [[species]] of bird in the typical broadbill [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Eurylaimidae]]. A small, distinctive species, it has a black head, breastband, and {{Birdgloss|upperparts}}, a white neckband, yellow streaking on the back and wings, and [[vinous]]-pink {{Birdgloss|underparts}} that turn yellow towards the belly. The beak is bright blue, with a green tip to the upper [[Beak#Mandibles|mandible]] and black edges. It shows some [[sexual dimorphism]], with the black breastband being incomplete in females.

Native to [[Brunei]], Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Singapore, and Thailand, it inhabits [[evergreen forest]], [[dipterocarp forest]], swamp forest, [[heath forest]], and [[Woodland edge|forest edge]], along with [[secondary forest]] and [[plantation]]s that contain large trees. Mainly inhabiting lowlands, the species is found up to elevations of {{cvt|1220|m|ft}}. The black-and-yellow broadbill is mainly [[Insectivore|insectivorous]], but also feeds on [[Mollusca|molluscs]] and incidentally takes fruit.

The black-and-yellow broadbill breeds during the dry season throughout its range, with both sexes helping build a large, untidy, pear-shaped nest out of moss, fungal [[Mycelium|mycelia]], and leaves. Eggs are laid in [[Clutch (eggs)|clutches]] of two or three, sometimes containing a fourth [[runt]] egg, and are [[Egg incubation|incubated]] by both sexes. The species is listed as [[Near-threatened species|near-threatened]] by the [[IUCN]] because of a decline in its population caused by [[habitat loss]].

==Taxonomy and systematics==
The black-and-yellow broadbill was described as ''Eurylaimus ochromalus'' by the British naturalist [[Stamford Raffles]] in 1822 based on specimens from Singapore.<ref name="Raffles">{{Cite book|last=Raffles|first=Stamford|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/13692#page/329/mode/1up|title=Second part of the descriptive catalogue of a zoological collection made in the island of Sumatra and its vicinity|series=[[Transactions of the Linnean Society of London]]|publisher=[[Linnean Society of London]]|year=1822|volume=13|location=London|pages=297–298|language=en|via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]|access-date=1 December 2021|archive-date=1 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201160750/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/13692#page/329/mode/1up|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Baker">{{Cite journal |last=Baker |first=E. C. Stuart |date=1917 |title=On behalf of Messrs. H. C. Robinson and C. B. Kloss, Exhibition of types and descriptions of new species of Malayan birds: – ''Garrulax pectoralis meridionalis'', ''Gecinus canus meridionalis'', ''Gecinus vittatus connectens'', ''Iyngipicus canicapillus suffusus'', ''Eurylaimus javanicus brookei'', ''Eurylaimus ochromalus kalamantan'', ''Serilophus lunatus stolidus'', ''Rhinocichla mitrata major'', ''Poliositta azurea nigriventer'', ''Ophrydomis albogularis moultoni'' |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/100942#page/283/mode/1up |url-status=live |journal=[[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]] |language=en |location=London |publisher=[[British Ornithologists' Club]] |volume=40 |page=15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201160753/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/100942#page/283/mode/1up |archive-date=1 December 2021 |access-date=1 December 2021 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]}}</ref> The generic name ''Eurylaimus'' comes from the [[Ancient Greek]] {{lang|grc|ευρυς}} ({{Transliteration|grc|eurus}}), meaning broad, and {{lang|grc|λαιμος}} ({{Transliteration|grc|laimos}}), meaning throat. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''ochromalus'' may come from either the Greek ''ōkhros'', meaning pale yellow, and ''melas'', meaning black, or ''ōkhromelas'', meaning [[jaundice]]d.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jobling|first=James A.|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names|publisher=[[Christopher Helm Publishers|Christopher Helm]]|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4|location=London|pages=154, 279|language=en}}</ref> Black-and-yellow broadbill is the official [[common name]] designated by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]].<ref name="ioc2">{{Cite web |title=NZ wrens, Sapayoa, broadbills, asities, pittas |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/nz_wrens/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231218155627/https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/nz_wrens/ |archive-date=18 December 2023 |access-date=2024-02-15 |website=IOC World Bird List}}</ref> Other common names for the species include black and white broadbill, black and yellow broadbill, and black-yellow broadbill.<ref>{{Cite web|title=''Eurylaimus ochromalus'' (Black-and-yellow Broadbill)|url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=C429744BA607CD0F|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924231917/http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=C429744BA607CD0F|archive-date=24 September 2011|access-date=2021-12-01|website=[[Avibase]]}}</ref> The species is called {{Lang|ms|takau kasturi}} in [[Malay language|Malay]], {{Transliteration|th|Nok Phaya Paak Kwaang lek}} in [[Thai language|Thai]],<ref name=":12">{{Cite book|last=Wells|first=David R.|title=The Birds of the Thai-Malay Peninsula: Passerines|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4081-3313-2|volume=2|location=London|language=en}}</ref> and {{Lang|tea|curɔɔw}} in [[Temiar language|Temiar]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Lim|first1=Teckwyn|last2=Quinton|first2=David P.|last3=Solano-Mena|first3=Alicia|last4=Yi Loo|first4=Yen|last5=Loke|first5=Vivienne P. W.|last6=Angah|first6=Rizuan|last7=Sudin|first7=Husin|last8=Tauhid|first8=Muhd|date=2018|title=Short notes–Temiar bird names.|url=https://figshare.com/articles/journal_contribution/6963116|journal=Malaysian Nature Journal|pages=21–24|doi=10.17608/k6.auckland.6963116.v1|issn=0025-1291|doi-access=free}}</ref>

The black-and-yellow broadbill is one of two species currently placed in the genus ''[[Eurylaimus]]'', in the typical broadbill [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Eurylaimidae|Eurylamidae]], a family of ten tropical species native to [[Southeast Asia]]''.<ref name="ioc2" />'' Based on a 2017 study by the Brazilian researcher Alexandre Selvatti and colleagues, its closest relative is the [[banded broadbill]]. These two species are most closely related to a [[clade]] formed by the [[Black-and-red broadbill|black-and-red]] and [[silver-breasted broadbill]]s, and all three genera form a [[sister clade]] to the genus ''[[Sarcophanops]]''. This clade is sister to one formed by the [[long-tailed broadbill]] and [[dusky broadbill]]. Both of these clades are sister to [[Grauer's broadbill]].<ref name="Selvatti-et-al" /> An earlier 2006 study by Robert Moyle and colleagues also found strong support for these relationships, but did not sample the [[wattled broadbill]].<ref name="Moyle">{{Cite journal|last1=Moyle|first1=R. G.|last2=Chesser|first2=R. T.|last3=Prum|first3=R. O.|last4=Schikler|first4=Peter|last5=Cracraft|first5=Joel|date=2006|title=Phylogeny and evolutionary history of Old World suboscine birds (Aves, Eurylaimides)|url=https://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/5822//v3/dspace/updateIngest/pdfs/N3544.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=3544|pages=483–499|issn=0003-0082|doi=10.1206/0003-0082(2006)3544[1:PAEHOO]2.0.CO;2|s2cid=15871486 }}</ref> The following cladogram shows [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] relationships among the Eurylaimidae, based on the 2017 study:{{Efn|The study did not include the [[w:Visayan broadbill|Visayan broadbill]], which was formerly considered [[w:conspecific|conspecific]] with the [[w:wattled broadbill|wattled broadbill]]. Additionally, it treated the [[w:grey-lored broadbill|grey-lored broadbill]] as being conspecific with the [[w:silver-breasted broadbill|silver-breasted broadbill]].<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Cottrell|first1=G. William|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14480346#page/23/mode/1up|title=Check-list of birds of the world|last2=Greenway|first2=James C.|last3=Mayr|first3=Ernst|last4=Paynter|first4=Raymond A.|last5=Peters|first5=James Lee|last6=Traylor|first6=Melvin A.|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|year=1951|volume=7|location=Cambridge|page=9|language=en|access-date=19 January 2022|archive-date=19 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119043215/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14480346#page/23/mode/1up|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Selvatti-et-al" />|name=}}<ref name="Selvatti-et-al">{{Cite journal|last1=Selvatti|first1=A. P.|last2=Galvão|first2=A.|last3=Pereira|first3=A. G.|last4=Pedreira Gonzaga|first4=L.|last5=Russo|first5=C. A. D. M.|date=2017|title=An African origin of the Eurylaimides (Passeriformes) and the successful diversification of the ground-foraging pittas (Pittidae)|journal=[[Molecular Biology and Evolution]]|volume=34|issue=2|pages=483–499|doi=10.1093/molbev/msw250|issn=1537-1719|pmid=28069777|doi-access=free}}</ref>

